11.body: This guide teaches how to download and install Bend through Rust, using Cargo, a tool used for managing packages. It may be necessary to have an internet connection to proceed with this guide.
11.title: Install

13.body: Install Windows Subsystem for Linux (WSL2) by following the official guide . After installing WSL2, open your WSL2 terminal and follow the Linux installation instructions below.
13.title: On Windows

14.body:
# Install Rust if you haven't it already.
curl --proto '=https' --tlsv1.2 -sSf https://sh.rustup.rs | sh # For the C version of Bend, use GCC. We recommend a version up to 12.x.
sudo apt install gcc For the CUDA runtime install the CUDA toolkit for Linux version 12.x.

15.body:

16.body:
Install HVM2 by running: # HVM2 is HOC's massively parallel Interaction Combinator evaluator.
cargo install hvm # This ensures HVM is correctly installed and accessible.
hvm --version Install Bend by running: # This command will install Bend
cargo install bend-lang # This ensures Bend is correctly installed and accessible.
bend --version By following the above steps, we can start using Bend. Now, let's proceed to Text Editors and finish preparing our setup for exploration.

18.body:
First of all, create a directory to store the bend files. It is recommended to use a dedicated directory to keep all exercises and examples, but feel free to do as you please. The three commands below will create a directory named 'bendExamples' and a file named 'hello_world.bend' inside the project directory. Use them in order: // Linux, Mac or WSL
mkdir bendExamples
cd bendExamples
touch hello_world.bend The .bend extension is what makes it a bend file. For example, a file that ends with .exe is an executable; .js is a JavaScript file; .rs is a Rust file, etc. If the commands were used correctly, the hello_world.bend file should be inside the bendExamples folder. So let's have some fun, CODING!

24.body: Making Decisions Based on Conditions in Bend a common way to implement this is by using conditional statements, such as if and else.
24.breadcrumbs: Patterns and Matching » if » IF Statements
24.title: IF Statements

25.body: The if-else structure allows our program to execute different blocks of code depending on whether a condition is true or false. def if_else(cond): if cond: return "condition is true" else: return "condition is false" Here, cond is the condition we are evaluating. If cond is true, the function returns "condition is true". Otherwise, it returns "condition is false".
25.breadcrumbs: Patterns and Matching » if » The Basic Structure of if-else
25.title: The Basic Structure of if-else

26.body: Unlike some languages where else may be optional, in Bend else is mandatory. This ensures that there is always an execution path, even if the initial condition is not met.
26.breadcrumbs: Patterns and Matching » if » Importance of else
26.title: Importance of else

27.body: In the above structure, cond should return a u24 (a 24-bit integer), where 0 represents false and any other value represents true. def if_else_u24(cond): if cond != 0: return "condition is true" else: return "condition is false" Chaining Conditions with elif For situations where we need to evaluate multiple conditions, we use elif. This allows us to create chains of conditions where several conditions are tested in sequence until one of them is true. def else_if(cond): if cond == 1: return 0 elif cond > 1: return 1 elif cond < 1: return 2 else: return 3 Here, we have a function that returns different values depending on the value of cond: If cond is true, it returns 0. If cond is greater than 1, it returns 1. If cond is less than 1, it returns 2. If none of the above conditions are true, it returns 3.
27.breadcrumbs: Patterns and Matching » if » The Condition

28.body: Switch statements offer a structured and efficient way to select among multiple conditions based on a specific value. In some programming languages, using switch statements can simplify the control flow logic compared to multiple if-else statements.

29.body: The switch construct is used to associate a variable name with the result of a given condition and branch to the case that matches its value.

3.body: A terminal can be described as an interface for users to communicate with the computer. They are our command-line interface, a place where we type commands and the computer process it. You can customize your terminal the way you want and feel most comfortable with. Command-lines in a terminal follow a "left to right" hierarchy, the left side always come first and the computer interprets them in this order. Before explaining terminal commands to you, there is a very important command that you need to understand, the sudo command. sudo is the abbreviation of "super user do" that, when used, allows a user to get privileges of another user (usually the super user) to securely perform specific tasks within the system in a administrator controllable manner. You will need to use the sudo command in a lot of cases.
3.breadcrumbs: Getting Started » Terminal » What is a Terminal

30.body: The cases must be listed from smallest to largest, starting at 0 and incrementing by 1.
30.breadcrumbs: Patterns and Matching » switch » Ordering of Cases
30.title: Ordering of Cases

31.body: The last case must be _, which catches all values not explicitly enumerated.
31.breadcrumbs: Patterns and Matching » switch » Default Case (_)
31.title: Default Case (_)

32.body: Switch statements can only be used with native numeric values. Let's examine a basic example: def switch_example(x): switch x: case 0: return 6 case 1: return 7 case _: return x - 2 In this example, the switch checks the value of x and returns a result based on the corresponding case: If x is 0, it returns 6. If x is 1, it returns 7. For all other values (_), it returns x - 2. In the last case, the value of the predecessor is available with the name bound_var-next_num, where bound_var is the variable defined by the condition and next_num is the expected value of the next case. Let's detail this with a more specific example.
32.breadcrumbs: Patterns and Matching » switch » Native Values
32.title: Native Values

33.body: We can see that the switch structure can be converted to a series of if-else statements: def switch_case(x): if x == 0: return 6 elif x == 1: return 7 else: return x - 2
33.breadcrumbs: Patterns and Matching » switch » Implementing Switch Using If-Else
33.title: Implementing Switch Using If-Else

34.body: Let's see how a switch can be equivalent to an if-else from the previous section: def if_else_equiv(condition): if condition == 0: # then branch return 1 else: # else branch return 0
34.breadcrumbs: Patterns and Matching » switch » Comparative Example
34.title: Comparative Example

35.body: def switch_equiv_expl(condition): switch condition == 0: # explicit case 0: # else branch return 0 case _: # then branch return 1 def switch_equiv_impl(condition): switch condition: # implicit case 0: return 1 case _: return 0 Both functions above implement the same logic but using different control structures.
35.breadcrumbs: Patterns and Matching » switch » Equivalent to Switch
35.title: Equivalent to Switch

36.body: Using switch can make your code clearer and more readable when dealing with many conditions and is more efficient than multiple if-else statements. It is a powerful control flow tool that complements traditional if-else structures.
36.title: Conclusion

42.body: The default case must be _, which catches all values not explicitly enumerated. Consider the definition of a type Option: type Option: None Some {value} def match_example(x): match x: case Option/None: return 0 case Option/Some: return x.value In this example, the variable x can be an instance of Option/Some or Option/None. The matching logic determines the value based on the constructor of x. If x is an instance of Option/None, 0 is returned. If x is an instance of Option/Some, the field value is returned.
42.breadcrumbs: Patterns and Matching » match » Default Case (_)
42.title: Default Case (_)

43.body: Consider a type Direction: type Direction: Up Down Left Right def direction_to_string(direction): match direction: case Direction/Up: return "Up" case Direction/Down: return "Down" case Direction/Left: return "Left" case Direction/Right: return "Right" In this example, direction_to_string converts a Direction value to a corresponding string.
43.breadcrumbs: Patterns and Matching » match » Detailed Example
43.title: Detailed Example

44.body: Consider a binary tree: type BTree: Leaf Node {value, left, right} def sum_tree(btree): match btree: case BTree/Leaf: return 0 case BTree/Node: return btree.value + sum_tree(btree.left) + sum_tree(btree.right) Here, sum_tree calculates the sum of all values in a binary tree: If tree is BTree/Leaf, it returns 0. If tree is BTree/Node, it sums the current node's value with the sums of the left and right subtrees.
44.breadcrumbs: Patterns and Matching » match » Nested Structures
44.title: Nested Structures

cd

Back: Moves to the previous folder. cd 'folderName' Through Files: Will take you to that folder specified. The command ls stands for "List Files", and lists the content of the current folder. Command Description ls Listing: Will show you a list of the files and folders in the current folder that you are in. ls -la Deeper Listing: Will show a more detailed version of the ls command, with it's hidden files or folders. The command mkdir , that stands for "Make Directory", creates a new folder. Command Description mkdir folderName Creating: Works by creating a folder with the specified name. For example:mkdir exampleFolder creates it with the name "exampleFolder" File related commands The command rm stands for "Remove", and removes the specified file or folder. Command Description rm fileName Removing Files: Removes the file specified in it. rm -r folderName Removing Folders: Removes a folder in the same way as mkdir creates it, you need to specify which folder you want to remove. This command is VERY DANGEROUS! If possible, DO NOT USE IT , there are a lot of memes on the internet from people using rm to delete important folders. Avoid everything that has the rm command on internet, otherwise, use it by your own discretion and responsibility! The command mvstands for "Move", and has two functionalities, to move and rename files or folders. Command Description mv fileName /folderName Moving things: Using command moves the fileName file to the folderName folder. In order for this command to work, it is needed to write the file name followed by the name of the directory that you want to send the file to. For example: mv bendFile.bend /newDirectory to move a file to a folder inside the current folder.mv bendFile.bend ../folderName to take a file to a folder in a previous folder by using "../" before the name of the folder. mv oldFileName newFileName Renaming things: The command changes the name of a file or folder to the name specified in the second parameter. For example:mv oldName.bend newName.bend to rename a file from "oldName.bend" to "newName.bend".mv oldbendFolder newbendFolder to rename a folder from "oldbendFolder" to "newbendFolder". The command touch can do a couple of complicated things, such as update file access and it's modification time. But, right now we are only gonna use it to create new files. Command Description touch Creating Flies: The command creates (if this file do not exists yet) a new file. For example: touch newfile.bend will create a .bend file with the specified name. 50.body: For fields annotated with ~ in the type definition, the fold function is implicitly called. Suppose a tree definition where the subtree fields are annotated with ~: type BTree: Leaf Node {value, ~left, ~right} Here, Node represents an internal tree node with a value and left and right subtrees, while Leaf represents a tree leaf.
50.breadcrumbs: Patterns and Matching » fold » Implicit fold Calls
50.title: Implicit fold Calls

51.body: With this definition, we can use the fold function implicitly. Let's create a fold that sums all the node values in the tree: def sum_btree(btree): fold btree: case BTree/Leaf: return 0 case BTree/Node: return btree.value + btree.left + btree.right In this example: If the tree matches Leaf, we return 0. If the tree matches Node, we sum the node's value with the results of the recursive fold calls on the left and right subtrees.
51.breadcrumbs: Patterns and Matching » fold » Fold Example
51.title: Fold Example

52.body: A fold statement is equivalent to an inline recursive function. The above example can be rewritten equivalently using an explicit recursive function: def fold(tree): match tree: case BTree/Leaf: return 0 case BTree/Node: return tree.value + fold(tree.left) + fold(tree.right)
52.breadcrumbs: Patterns and Matching » fold » Equivalence with Recursive Function
52.title: Equivalence with Recursive Function

53.body: Fold statements provide an elegant way to reduce complex data structures like trees by recursively applying a function. By allowing field binding and implicit fold calls, this structure facilitates clear and efficient manipulation and aggregation of data.
53.title: Conclusion

54.body: The bend construction in Bend is a powerful and versatile tool used to create recursive data structures and emulate iterative processes in a declarative and functional manner. It allows you to define a recursive process that builds a complex structure step-by-step until a specific condition is met.
54.breadcrumbs: Patterns and Matching » bend » The bend Construction in Bend
54.title: The bend Construction in Bend

55.body: The bend construction initializes a recursive process with an initial state and iterates until a specified condition is met. It is similar to an embedded recursive function. bend <state_variables>: when <condition>: <recursive_operations> else: <termination_operations>
55.breadcrumbs: Patterns and Matching » bend » Basic Structure
55.title: Basic Structure

56.body: The state variables are initialized in the header of the bend. There can be multiple state variables, each with an initial value.
56.breadcrumbs: Patterns and Matching » bend » Initialization of State Variables
56.title: Initialization of State Variables

57.body: The state variables are treated immutably, ensuring that each recursive step has a consistent and predictable state.
57.breadcrumbs: Patterns and Matching » bend » Immutable State
57.title: Immutable State

58.body: The bend starts a recursive construction, initializing a state and executing a block of code until a stopping condition is met.
58.breadcrumbs: Patterns and Matching » bend » Structured Recursion
58.title: Structured Recursion

59.body: The bend construction offers explicit control over recursion, allowing you to clearly define when the recursion should continue and when it should stop.
59.breadcrumbs: Patterns and Matching » bend » Controlled Recursion
59.title: Controlled Recursion

6.body: Welcome to Bend, an innovative and versatile programming language designed to empower developers with simplicity and efficiency. Bend aims to blend the best features of modern programming paradigms with an intuitive syntax that makes coding a delightful experience.

60.body: The when clause defines the condition under which the recursion continues. If the condition is true, the recursive operations are executed. If the condition is false, the termination operations are executed.
60.breadcrumbs: Patterns and Matching » bend » Continuation Condition
60.title: Continuation Condition

61.body: Within the when clause, the fork function is used to call the bend recursively with new values for the state variables. The number of arguments passed to fork must match the number of state variables.
61.breadcrumbs: Patterns and Matching » bend » Recursive Operations
61.title: Recursive Operations

62.body: When the condition is no longer true, the termination operations are executed in the else clause. This clause defines the final behavior and values returned by the bend construction.
62.breadcrumbs: Patterns and Matching » bend » Termination Operations
62.title: Termination Operations

63.body: It allows building recursive data structures by adding layers or branches at each recursive call.
63.breadcrumbs: Patterns and Matching » bend » Incremental Construction
63.title: Incremental Construction

64.body: The ability to manipulate multiple state variables and construct different types of data structures makes the bend a flexible and powerful tool for various applications.
64.title: Flexibility

65.body: Besides creating recursive data structures, the bend can be used to simulate iterative processes.
65.title: Versatility

66.breadcrumbs: Patterns and Matching » bend » Usage Examples
66.title: Usage Examples

67.body: def create_tree(): bend x = 0: when x < 3: left = fork(x + 1) right = fork(x + 1) tree = ![left, right] else: tree = !x return tree This code creates a binary tree: Initializes x = 0. Continues recursion while x < 3. Within the when clause, fork(x + 1) recursively calls the bend with an incremented value of x. Creates tree nodes with ![left, right]. Ends recursion with !x when x >= 3.
67.breadcrumbs: Patterns and Matching » bend » Example 1: Creating a Binary Tree
67.title: Example 1: Creating a Binary Tree

68.body:
The bend is general enough to emulate a loop by recursively iterating over a state until a termination condition is met. For example, this Python program: sum = 0
idx = 0
while idx < 10: sum = idx + sum idx = idx + 1 can be rewritten using bend: def loop(): bend idx = 0: when idx < 10: sum = idx + fork(idx + 1) else: sum = 0 return sum This code emulates a loop that sums integers from 0 to 9 using recursion: Initializes idx = 0. Continues recursion while idx < 10. Iterates over idx, incrementing it by 1. Computes the sum of integers from 0 to 9, adding the current idx value to the sum of the next iteration. Ends recursion returning 0 when idx >= 10.
68.breadcrumbs: Patterns and Matching » bend » Example 2: Sum Calculation with Emulated Loop
68.title: Example 2: Sum Calculation with Emulated Loop

69.body: The bend can handle multiple state variables simultaneously, enabling complex recursive processes. def mult_var(): bend x = 1, y = 2: when x < 10 & y < 20: result = fork(x + 1, y + 2) else: result = (x, y) return result This code creates a tuple: Initializes x = 1 and y = 2. Continues recursion while x < 10 and y < 20. Increments x and y differently at each recursive step. Ends recursion returning the values of (x, y) when one of the conditions is no longer true.
69.breadcrumbs: Patterns and Matching » bend » Multiple State Variables
69.title: Multiple State Variables

7.body: Bend is a high-level programming language developed by HigherOrderCO. It is designed with a focus on readability, performance, and ease of use. Bend allows developers to write clean and maintainable code while leveraging powerful abstractions to manage complexity.
7.breadcrumbs: Getting Started » About bend » What is Bend?
7.title: What is Bend?

70.body: The bend construction can be used to build complex recursive data structures, such as trees, linked lists, and graphs. def repeat(target): bend n = 0: when n < target: list = List/Cons(n, fork(n + 1)) else: list = [] return list This code creates a linked list: Initializes n = 0. Continues recursion while n < target. Creates list nodes with [n, (n + 1), ..., (n < target)]. Ends recursion with [] when n >= target.
70.breadcrumbs: Patterns and Matching » bend » Recursive Data Structures
70.title: Recursive Data Structures
